segments.text: Okay, I'd like to start out asking you where you came from before you moved here.
Okay, and why did you come?
Did you want to come down here?
Okay.
And what kind of work are you doing right now?
Various.
I'm a home builder, a real ranger.
So you build a lot of houses in Bryan?
Bryan College Station.
I build a number of good places right now at Bryan College Station.
Okay, have you ever been anything about politics or anything?
Yeah, city council.
City council?
Got beat.
Got beat.
Oh, well.
Okay.
Okay.
Can you tell me about anything about your children?
Do they like this area, the country?
Like I said, we moved here in 1959.
You like the people here in Fort Worth?
Oh, yeah.
Period.
I lived in Dallas, and that's where I was born.
I don't like the people in Dallas.
I love this part of the country.
Yeah, I think I like it.
geography of the country trees and so forth i think the small town atmosphere though i think we're losing what do you think uh about the changes in technology
for advancement of the city.
Can you tell me about how it's grown, how it was whenever you came here back in 1959, and the progress that it's taken?
I don't know exactly what you mean.
Technology?
Any industry?
What effects maybe the college may have had?
And businesses?
Okay, when we moved to Bryan, I don't know how much you want me to elaborate on this stuff, but we moved to Bryan in 1959.
Bryan Field was closed in 1958.
This is undoubtedly the deadest town you've not ever been in.
There was property for rent for sale all over town, all the sports you wanted to play for.
We lived in a nice three-bedroom house.
We rented for a few months.
$75 a month.
And we bought a three-bedroom, two-bath, new brick home for a small one, about $150,000.
No down payment.
It was a case in mind.
It was an elderly family.
They accepted no down payment.
They just wanted to rent it off.
The next thing in was college then.
The number of students had been the same for a year.
It wasn't growing.
Everybody was scared to death with it.
The economy was just going to go to nothing because of that base load.
And about two or three years later, it started making the change.
A&M started growing a little.
The attitudes of people just seemed to change.
And right now, basically, my opinion, the Bryan College Station is, you know, almost totally dependent on A&M.
The industry that's covered the town has been mental for the size of town it is.
We've got two or three small industries, but A&M is, as A&M goes, like me.
Okay, how did the Bryan College Station, did they want the college to turn co-ed where girls can come in?
I think.
Was that a big issue?
uh... uh...
requirement about being in the court at the same time?
As far as I was concerned on the college, I had no preference.
I didn't go to A&M or anything like that.
Other than for business reasons.
Do you think Bryan College Station will have enough facilities, apartments and all to fulfill
All the students?
Oh, basically we'll probably build them as fast as possible right now.
It's just going to be a matter of time before people all went to work and I was having enough.
It'll be a matter of time before we have too many.
Because I know next semester they're turning down, all the dorms are filled up, and they turned down 2,300 freshmen that are coming in.
I just want to know if they have room for that 2,300.
That's discretionary.
No, I'm sure that has a lot more to turn them down.
They just didn't have a place to live.
But I can say that the private sector normally reacts to these things and overreacts.
I don't think we can put any city around.
Austin's a good example of where it's going.
It's probably going to any city, a small city in, say, Texas.
And now they're way over the other apartment houses and everything else.
Let me ask you something about your line of work and building and all.
How come you don't build more than just two-story complexes?
Couldn't you build maybe four or five-story complexes to hold more people?
Well, back up a bit, I'm not an apartment builder.
You're not an apartment builder?
We started building duplexes.
Now, duplexes are basically houses.
And that's an hour round of thinking.
We'll build a lot of duplexes, but still each individual big duplex will be $35,000, $70,000.
There's not a $2 to $5 million project.
When I say we, I'm talking about my company.
We're not going to do that kind of thing.
We're not a commercial apartment building.
And why though?
I just got into this man.
Oh, you did?
I've never been in one yet.
Okay.
So, since you've been here quite a while now, and you know quite a few people around this area, you communicate with them, the people that came in, are they just
mostly middle-income people, or do you see a lot of real wealthy people coming into this area wanting to live here?
No, we see some, probably maybe a little more than normal.
We see upper-middle-class people, but by far the majority is the majority of people in this area.
Again, do they end up there?
I'd say we sell...
Probably 60% of our house made more than Ph.D. Yeah, I was going to say, I imagine a lot of these big expensive houses are probably just... Well, not really expensive anymore.
The small, little small houses are more expensive.
Yeah.
And it takes Ph.D. almost to afford them.
If you get away from A&M, you don't have that many management people in the private sector.
Okay.
Would you tell me any relations that you have with other families in the ground?
Do you have any relationships, any contact with
Say, for instance, the mayor and the councilman.
I know them all.
You know them all?
I shouldn't say I know them all really well.
I know several of them really well.
How come you don't run for city council?
I figure it out when I serve from once in a while.
Once you're a fool, twice you're stupid.
One reason I'm not living in the city of Brighton
What was your sole purpose for moving out of the city?
Just to live out in the country.
I had lived in the country close to Brian, a lot closer than we are now, but I lived and we lived in the country for six out of the past seven years before I run for city council.
I run for city council for one reason, and that was that Brian, like I said, Brian, my home, not Brian, but the college station really, and...
The growth of the area was shifted to College Station because the city of Bryan is just not doing enough for the value of children.
There's subdivisions and so forth across the bypasses.
And we were ready to pick the right group of businesses.
We were interested in Bryan.
Their business was Bryan.
And I was talking to the governor on that.
Do you ever see today where College Station might be bigger than Bryan because of the college?
Well, of course the university is there and the big growth right now is in College Station.

Getting further and further away from the university, actually, there's many places in Bryan you can build and develop out that's closer to A&M than, say, Southwood Valley, where most of the dollar stations are going now.
It's a long way from A&M to Southwood Valley.
And right back, it depends on what the fish in the city of Bryan do, to a big extent.
If they get these through streets to these areas to open up,
I think, now I don't want this going everywhere, but I think there's two factors that's going to affect and slow down the growth in College Station.
One is the tax base at College Station is going to get a hold of one of these days.
And then there's the big, big, big industry there and they pay no taxes.
These two are there for you, all the stuff you're all staying in.
So there's no tax base out there.
There's no industry out there to speak to.
That and then the Thai people that keep getting the city government and the Thai people running out for mayor and council and so forth at the college station.
They're highly educated people.
Their theories on city planning, development, and so forth is, in my opinion, is all textbook.
I think the city of Bryan officials are all waking up to some of these needs and I think they can see what's going on real easy right now.
So you think the
political control in College Station is kind of a little stronger than that in Bryan?
What do you think?
I think the growth in College Station up to this point has been in spite, not because of political control.
I think political control keeps turning over the way it is in College Station the way it looks to me that it's going to be in the future.
You think it works?
I mean, they're going to have, we can't all get flat or something approved.
I'm not a developer.
Basically, I build houses where somebody else will develop the land.
Most of it we're developing right now because we run out of a good place to build.
Not because we want to develop.
We think, you know, our business is house building.
We need somebody else to do the development.
But I know from talking to developers and the problems they're having out there with...

politics don't do where I think it's possible they'll do.
They don't just tie it up.
I think there's a good chance of College Station being a big city.
It just seems like so much more money is running into the city.
I've been here for a year and they've built
So many new restaurants.
Shopping centers.
Shopping centers.
And I just haven't seen any new building.
Maybe a little bit, but not as much.
Twice as much in College Station as I've seen in Bryan.
And if they keep up that pace, I don't know.
If they keep up that pace, it won't take a long time to do it either.
You look at the population of two cities in 1980.
Compared to 1979, it's going to shock a lot of people.
That's not including the students?
The students who live off that campus got to be counted.
When they talk about this population, whether you include the students or not, or the ones who live off the campus, I don't know how you couldn't count.
I've already heard that with the students that do live in there already, there's around 30,000.
Do you think that's true?
Yeah.
The science is 17,000.
There was 25,000 students in there.
We're expecting 27,000 to 30,000 next semester.
Of course, a lot of those students do live in Brown.
You know, there's one fallacy to all of this.
We all keep talking about, you know, all the buildings going on College Station, all the buildings going on College Station, when you get the building permits on residences.
Brian has led College Station each one of the last two years.
You know, and all the year before that.
Where I would have thought before I read those, each year the College Station would have been led by Brian.
You said you moved here after the Air Force Base was closed down?
Yeah, next year.
So you don't know much about it.
You want to break it down and say it to me.
You know, from what I heard.
Do you think religion has any sort of effect?
in the culture of the city?
Does it have a kind of a dominant control, like politics might?
Oh, I don't think so.
I think that Bryan is probably, you know, a pretty short church on any community.
But I don't think it has one.
There's nothing like Dallas being mostly all baptismal.
That's what we're going to do too.
You mean to study the people out here?
We're taking a field trip.
this next month in April.
And I have to plan, also besides this, I have to plan a field trip for my plan as all the majors do.
Caldwell is one of the cities I was going to go to.
We're going to Caldwell, and from there to Minnesota, and to Anderson, and back.
And we're going to study not only the cultural features, the people, but also the geologic features.
study how, what geologic features might have had an influence on people, and physical features, and how the Brazos River might have had an impact on the farm and irrigation, or whatever.
You know, I've been really interested, since it moved over here, to see all our neighbors over here check.
And, you never have to take the time, and all libraries, and so forth, somewhere I'll find a book about it.
Have you ever talked to them and asked why they came here?
Yeah, most of them don't know.
Their grandparents, grandparents, one of them, would come over.
And the other night, most of us got our version of history.
We just don't know what happened.
I know one of the elder guys had a chance to get on the study, but the elder guy said, get on this place.
Uh, her husband's parents met and married on the boat one way or the other.
Just a couple days.
They married on a boat?
Married on a ship.
You don't know what, oh.
Yeah.
Okay, um, could you tell me your view of, um,
What improvements you think need to be made in this area?
That's a hard question.
Hard question.
Financial is better than community or cultural is better than community or what?
Financial.
A lot more about that.
Okay.
Oh, I don't know.
I think
The biggest thing, if the people at Bryan and College Station want their cities to continue to grow like they've done and have this dynamic growth,
and become a city trade area, a trade center type thing.
The thing they're going to have to do is they're going to have to do industry.
We've got to live off of that industry so long.
A&M is going to reach a saturation point one of these days.
It's going to get so big within the idea.
One of the reasons for coming to A&M is it's going to be complex.
You know, I think people like Jack, I think Jack Williams probably done more riding the car station than any other one man there's been.
They can talk about the politicians and the media and all this.
What did Jack Williams do?
He put A&M on the map.
Yeah.
The last, what, the last five years has done, what, 14,000, 25,000, whatever it is, but... What kind of things did he do to pay money?
I don't think that's going to end out there.
I know he is cooperating with the business community and so forth.
I want to serve my time on the Chamber of Commerce.
And if there's anything we want any help with.
Okay, so you're saying that we need more industry?
We need some diversified industry here instead of just A&M.
I thought maybe...
Most people around here, I thought farming was an important...
It is.
But farmers here before...
The farming... Agriculture puts a lot of money into it.
Brian.
But agriculture won't make Brian grow.
The farmer out here, he's well off.
Brian's $10,000.
I think those towns go a lot easier to buy a main street than a small one.
But agriculture has a tremendous impact on the banks, the trade, the stores, and so forth.
But the farming's not going to grow, and it's not going to diminish.
It's going to stay pretty static.
And I imagine the size of a acreage farm in Brazos Bottom hasn't changed enough to speak of it.
But it has a lot more impact financially.
Imagine the cost of transporting their crops to a main market.
It's pretty expensive isn't it?
Or do they do it here in Bryan?
Basically, until a few years ago, Bradson's Bottom, and that's what, when you're talking about farming, you're talking about Bradson's Bottom and the rest of it.
Basically, it's livestock.
You know, the Tabor community and places like this, they used to farm.
It's all livestock in that place before I come here.
Man, farming, it was all cotton.
Now they farm grain and so forth, and they don't have a place to put it around here.
They have to transport something along the elevator.
I know over out near the one out here on Highway 21.
There's a small one.
I come from a farming area in Mexico.
How come they quit producing cotton?
They didn't make any money.
They didn't make any money?
A lot of them couldn't have gotten back even this year.
They went up to them.
Farming is a hard way to make a living.
Do you have any
Have you had many of your friends or relatives around here that have moved away?
I don't have any relatives around here.
No, you know, or a few that have had better jobs off of someone else or something, but a lot more.
We know and see basically the same people we've been seeing for 10 or 15 years.
There had been very few of them.
And there had not been any of them who didn't dislike the idea of having to move to Bryan.
That's true.
And they moved all the way to North Carolina and Alabama, down to Texas Coast.

One of them is an actual officer manager.
They moved over two years.
Another one was the administrator of our hospital.
We've got a bigger hospital.
Another one was a football field.
And they were a good friend.
And we still see them and hear from them and so forth.
And I'll be able to keep saying that as they get back around.
That's what I was going to ask.
OK.
